-Look at the card you played, Nina.

463
00:46:37,127 --> 00:46:41,006 
-Pay attention, girl.
-Our team thanks you.

464
00:46:41,215 --> 00:46:42,591 
It's a gift for us.

465
00:46:42,841 --> 00:46:44,927 
Come on, give it to me.

466
00:46:45,010 --> 00:46:48,388 
Honey, the game isn't over.

467
00:46:49,014 --> 00:46:51,350 
-You lost.
-Dad, Mom.

468
00:46:51,475 --> 00:46:55,270 
There's no going back,
you've played your card.

469
00:46:55,395 --> 00:46:56,605 
I'm searching for an apartment.

470
00:47:02,152 --> 00:47:03,362 
What do you mean?

471
00:47:04,571 --> 00:47:08,158 
I thought I should tell you
before I decide anything.

472
00:47:12,120 --> 00:47:13,622 
Decide what, Nina?

473
00:47:15,123 --> 00:47:18,585 
But, Nina, are you thinking
about living by yourself?

474
00:47:19,294 --> 00:47:23,173 
No, Dad. I'll live with a friend
and we're gonna split the rent.

475
00:47:25,634 --> 00:47:29,179 
-But how's that gonna work?
-I don't know about that.

476
00:47:31,098 --> 00:47:34,101 
That will have a cost.
How much is that?

477
00:47:35,060 --> 00:47:36,270 
Well, Mom.

478
00:47:36,937 --> 00:47:39,898 
-800 reais at most.
-Too expensive, Nina.

479
00:47:40,399 --> 00:47:42,484 
-Dad, don't start.
-Don't start?

480
00:47:42,568 --> 00:47:46,613 
I said 800 reais at most.
I'm searching for cheaper places too.

481
00:47:46,947 --> 00:47:49,783 
That's not easy, Nina. Not easy.

482
00:47:53,328 --> 00:47:56,248 
And who is this friend, Nina?

483
00:47:56,331 --> 00:47:58,792 
-Where did you meet?
-It's Joana, Mom.

484
00:47:59,793 --> 00:48:01,086 
We met in college.

485
00:48:01,628 --> 00:48:03,672 
And how are you
gonna pay for this, Nina?

486
00:48:04,214 --> 00:48:06,967 
I'll keep on tutoring.

487
00:48:07,259 --> 00:48:11,138 
I'm also looking for other things to do.
And I'm almost getting an internship.

488
00:48:11,221 --> 00:48:13,557 
Nina, you should be patient, honey.

489
00:48:14,099 --> 00:48:16,518 
-Graduate first.
-I'm almost graduating, Dad.

490
00:48:16,602 --> 00:48:18,103 
Then do it first.

491
00:48:18,770 --> 00:48:21,732 
-Then you get a boyfriend.
-Nonsense, Dad.

492
00:48:21,815 --> 00:48:25,027 
-Then you get married.
-Who said I wanna get married?

493
00:48:25,110 --> 00:48:26,194 
You don't?

494
00:48:26,278 --> 00:48:28,322 
So, for me to leave I have to get married?

495
00:48:28,405 --> 00:48:30,032 
-Why are you leaving?
-I won't get married.

496
00:48:30,115 --> 00:48:31,867 
-You have everything here.
-I want my freedom.

497
00:48:31,950 --> 00:48:34,036 
More freedom than you already have?

498
00:48:34,119 --> 00:48:37,247 
-Dad, it's not like that.
-How come it isn't?

499
00:48:38,165 --> 00:48:40,584 
-I wanna leave, that's all.
-Leaving…

500
00:48:40,667 --> 00:48:42,586 
-you're just a child.
-A child, Dad?

501
00:48:42,669 --> 00:48:45,756 
-How would that work?
-You keep treating me as a child.

502
00:48:45,839 --> 00:48:49,551 
-Two girls living in an apartment.
-What's the problem?

503
00:48:49,635 --> 00:48:52,679 
-And what if something happens?
-What would happen? It's safe.

504
00:48:52,763 --> 00:48:55,098 
-Who would take care of you?
-I can take care of myself.

505
00:48:55,182 --> 00:48:59,478 
Enough! Enough! For God's sake.

506
00:48:59,728 --> 00:49:03,690 
You already screwed the game up.
What a fucked-up Tuesday.

507
00:49:04,733 --> 00:49:07,819 
Nina, you find a way
to bring this girl here.

508
00:49:07,903 --> 00:49:09,821 
-What for?
-What for, Nina?

509
00:49:09,905 --> 00:49:13,992 
Girl, you aren't uncared for.
You have a mother, a father, a brother.

510
00:49:14,201 --> 00:49:16,662 
You think you can come in here
and just tell us you're leaving?

511
00:49:17,204 --> 00:49:19,790 
It's important to bring her here,

512
00:49:19,873 --> 00:49:21,416 
-right, Deivinho?
-Yeah.

513
00:49:21,500 --> 00:49:22,501 
Right, Wellington?

514
00:49:22,584 --> 00:49:24,544 
I wanna know about the game,
whose turn is it?

515
00:49:24,628 --> 00:49:25,671 
Your turn.

516
00:49:38,225 --> 00:49:40,560 
Why didn't you tell me
you were gonna leave?

517
00:49:43,438 --> 00:49:47,567 
I wasn't sure yet, Deivinho.
I’m still not sure.

518
00:49:50,987 --> 00:49:52,364 
Are you gonna move too far?

519
00:49:53,824 --> 00:49:54,783 
Maybe.

520
00:49:56,451 --> 00:49:58,328 
Downtown or the East Side.

521
00:50:01,623 --> 00:50:03,583 
But we'll see each other
all the time, Deivinho.

522
00:50:04,584 --> 00:50:06,211 
I'll always be with you.

523
00:50:07,462 --> 00:50:09,715 
Seeing you play soccer, becoming a star.

524
00:50:15,971 --> 00:50:19,057 
Nina, do you think dad would be mad
if I didn't play soccer anymore?

525
00:50:22,060 --> 00:50:23,395 
Don't you wanna play?

526
00:50:28,150 --> 00:50:30,944 
I don't know if I wanna become
a professional player.

527
00:50:35,365 --> 00:50:37,159 
Then talk to dad, Deivinho.

528
00:50:37,659 --> 00:50:39,494 
He can't make you do
anything you don't want to.

529
00:50:39,870 --> 00:50:44,291 
It's not that I want to stop playing,
I just think about doing other stuff too.

530
00:50:46,626 --> 00:50:48,962 
Yeah? What stuff?

531
00:50:52,966 --> 00:50:53,925 
What is it?

532
00:50:56,136 --> 00:50:58,513 
You'll think it's stupid,
I can’t tell you.

533
00:50:58,638 --> 00:51:00,766 
Tell me, don't be silly.

534
00:51:04,394 --> 00:51:08,523 
My dream is to become an astrophysicist
and go on the Mars One mission.

535
00:51:11,193 --> 00:51:14,029 
Mars One? What mission is that?

536
00:51:15,113 --> 00:51:20,452 
It's a mission that will happen in 2030.
Humans will try to colonize Mars.

537
00:51:24,706 --> 00:51:25,874 
Wow, Deivinho.

538
00:51:27,250 --> 00:51:28,710 
I don't even know what to say.

539
00:51:29,711 --> 00:51:32,339 
Is that what you want?
To go to Mars?

540
00:51:32,923 --> 00:51:36,760 
I'm even building
a telescope to observe better.

541
00:51:38,970 --> 00:51:40,305 
A telescope?

542
00:51:41,473 --> 00:51:46,311 
-I knew you'd think it's stupid.
-No, Deivinho. I don't think that.

543
00:51:47,187 --> 00:51:50,106 
It's beautiful. A beautiful dream.

544
00:51:51,358 --> 00:51:53,318 
I laughed because I never
heard you talking like that.

545
00:52:02,244 --> 00:52:05,413 
You wanna go to Mars
and worry about me moving far away?

546
00:52:11,586 --> 00:52:13,046 
Don't forget about me, okay?

547
00:52:28,478 --> 00:52:29,479 
Never, Deivinho.

548
00:52:39,072 --> 00:52:42,117 
Hey, go get the ball, boy.

549
00:52:42,951 --> 00:52:44,244 
Come on, Deivinho,

550
00:52:45,662 --> 00:52:48,290 
You're just walking there.
Don't do that, son.

551
00:52:56,631 --> 00:53:00,051 
Go get it, Deivinho. Come on, boy.

552
00:53:13,356 --> 00:53:15,317 
The right wing was trying
to pass you the ball

553
00:53:15,400 --> 00:53:18,320 
and you didn't pay attention.
You lost the ball twice, Deivinho.

554
00:53:19,988 --> 00:53:22,908 
Man up. Come on.
Pay attention to the game.

555
00:53:24,367 --> 00:53:26,745 
What's wrong, Deivinho?
Are you listening to me?

556
00:53:27,037 --> 00:53:29,122 
You're not paying attention.
Deivinho?

557
00:53:36,171 --> 00:53:40,592 
If they disarm the attack,
they're the best in the league.

558
00:53:40,717 --> 00:53:43,094 
-They just have to score, Dad.
-Yeah, but…

559
00:53:43,386 --> 00:53:46,056 
-Dad? Mom?
-Hey honey.

560
00:53:46,723 --> 00:53:48,725 
Hi, young lady.

561
00:53:48,934 --> 00:53:51,603 
-So, you are…
-Joana.

562
00:53:52,687 --> 00:53:55,106 
-This is my mom, Tércia.
-It's a pleasure.

563
00:53:55,190 --> 00:53:58,360 
Welcome.
Our daughter's friend is our friend too.

564
00:53:58,443 --> 00:53:59,861 
Thank you.

565
00:53:59,945 --> 00:54:03,156 
-This is my dad, Wellington.
-How are you? Nice to meet you.

566
00:54:03,365 --> 00:54:06,076 
Nina, if I knew
you were bringing a fan of Atlético,

567
00:54:06,368 --> 00:54:07,953 
I'd have saved on the fireworks.

568
00:54:08,036 --> 00:54:12,666 
The girl will be terrified here.

569
00:54:13,708 --> 00:54:16,086 
-Sit down, honey.
-Excuse me.

570
00:54:18,004 --> 00:54:19,422 
And you must be Deivinho.

571
00:54:21,424 --> 00:54:23,426 
Nina talks a lot about you.

572
00:54:25,095 --> 00:54:28,974 
Do you want some water,
coffee, juice, soda?

573
00:54:29,224 --> 00:54:32,143 
-Juice would be fine.
-I'll make you a lemonade.

574
00:54:32,227 --> 00:54:36,064 
-No need. It can be a soda then.
-No, it'll take just a minute.

575
00:54:36,231 --> 00:54:39,567 
You eat some pudding now.
It's a family recipe.

576
00:54:39,651 --> 00:54:41,653 
-I think you'll like it. Excuse me.
-Thank you.

577
00:54:43,613 --> 00:54:45,657 
-Make yourself at home.
-Thank you.

578
00:55:02,924 --> 00:55:07,053 
Come on. Come on.

579
00:55:08,304 --> 00:55:10,348 
Damn it. Come on.

580
00:55:10,724 --> 00:55:12,392 
What the hell?

581
00:55:12,684 --> 00:55:14,060 
I give up.

582
00:55:14,144 --> 00:55:16,021 
This guy looks like
he's got two right feet.

583
00:55:17,022 --> 00:55:18,481 
What is it, honey?

584
00:55:22,027 --> 00:55:24,612 
-What a shitty game.
-Deivinho seems off.

585
00:56:25,965 --> 00:56:28,343 
Goal! Goal!

586
00:56:28,676 --> 00:56:29,969 
Atlético!

587
00:56:31,346 --> 00:56:33,264 
What about the fireworks, Mr. Wellington?

588
00:56:36,559 --> 00:56:39,395 
-Fuck, Cruzeiro! Motherfucker!
-Hey.

589
00:56:44,526 --> 00:56:47,612
{\an8}<i>What should be done about the fact that</i>
<i>our kids lag woefully far behind</i>

590
00:56:47,946 --> 00:56:50,532
{\an8}<i>children in other countries in the areas</i>
<i>of physics and mathematics?</i>

591
00:56:50,615 --> 00:56:51,866
{\an8}<i>You know what my first reply is?</i>

592
00:56:52,784 --> 00:56:55,703
{\an8}<i>As a parent? Get out of their way?</i>

593
00:56:56,996 --> 00:56:58,414
{\an8}<i>When your kid… You're born</i>

594
00:56:58,498 --> 00:57:00,458 
<i>a scientist. What does a scientist do?</i>
<i>We look up and say,</i>

595
00:57:00,542 --> 00:57:02,669 
<i>"I wonder what that is?</i>
<i>Let me go find out."</i>

596
00:57:02,752 --> 00:57:06,381 
<i>-Right.</i>
<i>-Let me poke it. Let me break it!</i>

597
00:57:06,506 --> 00:57:09,968 
<i>So, you talk about events that can cause</i>
<i>the end of the world.</i>

598
00:57:10,051 --> 00:57:12,470 
<i>Does this knowledge</i>
<i>keep you awake at night?</i>

599
00:57:12,554 --> 00:57:14,931 
<i>Yes! Yes.</i>

600
00:57:17,642 --> 00:57:21,521
{\an8}LECTURE AND Q&A WITH NEIL DEGRASSE TYSON.

